g reflection, which makes me think about ObjectStreamClass in Java serialization. By directly using ObjectInputStream to read crafted bytes, I can invoke readObject on a class and create an instance without a constructor. Then, I could serialize the object and restore it using writeObject. Crafting streams might seem hacky, but it seems both practical and necessary for this task. Still, I wonder if substituting class names in this way is supported behavior.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering serialization options**\\n\\nI’m exploring the possibility of serializing a dynamic proxy, but it seems I need to work with JCEElGamalPublicKey, which implements ElGamalPublicKey and extends Serializable through Key. Although it doesn’t declare Serializable directly, Key does, which means serialization is supported. I’m considering using `sun.misc.Unsafe.allocateInstance`, but that involves reflection. Alternatively, I could use `ObjectInputStream` to deserialize by matching a descriptor with a local surrogate. I think `resolveClass` can return a class as long as the serialVersionUID matches, so I need to test this mentally.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining deserialization approaches**\\n\\nI’m looking into deserializing with a custom ObjectInputStream where `resolveClass` can return JCEElGamalPublicKey.class if the descriptor name is a surrogate. This might invoke the JCE readObject, and it seems like I'm not using direct reflection but rather the serialization API. It seems somewhat supported, as it tests deserialization compatibility from a stream with the same layout but a different name. There’s also the need for the writeObject method; once I have the target object, I can serialize it normally, even if it’s not in the library package.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_ubM1JMQSDKo1MVFshUPlSiMX|fc_0e99f899ffd06e4f016a10e29550e0819d98ffeaca85376bab", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find tests/src/org.bouncycastle/bcprov